  "prompt": "Do you burn more calories swimming or running?",
  "response": "The number of calories burned during swimming or running depends on several factors, including the intensity of the activity, the duration, your body weight, and your fitness level. However, in general:\n\n**Running** typically burns more calories than swimming **when comparing the same amount of time and intensity**. For example:\n\n- A 155-pound person running at 6 mph (a 10-minute mile) burns approximately **704 calories per hour**.\n- The same person swimming freestyle at a moderate pace burns about **493 calories per hour**.\n\nHowever, swimming can be more calorie-efficient **perceived effort** because it engages more muscle groups and is a low-impact activity, which may allow you to exercise longer without as much strain on your joints. Additionally, swimming in cold water can increase calorie burn due to the body working to maintain its temperature.\n\nIf you're looking to maximize calorie burn, high-intensity running or sprinting will generally burn the most calories in the shortest amount of time. But for overall fitness, injury prevention, and sustainability, swimming is an excellent option. The best choice depends on your goals, preferences, and physical condition!",
